Chicago July 20 1888

Mr B. Stone Esq
General Manager BR2 RR City
Dear Sir:
Following please find report of Operation D.D.
Saturday July 14'88
To-day at National Hotel.
There were a great many callers to-day to see  (([Hage?})) and Murphy and among them was Bowles' Brother who had a long consultation with Roger in the Hall near Hage's room.  J.J Bowles comes from Logansport Indiana they are all very bitter against the U.S Commissioner in the way they claim he ruled against them there were several (([junknown])) few were here who seem to take great interest in the trial and who are very bitter against Kelley and all who are reported to have made confessions -after the trial before the Commissioner Hages' room was crowded with them all expressing their opinion as to the result
Completed

of the trial a man named David who comes from (([unknown})) saying Boys now is the time to stick, for if your weaker now we are gone, when Hage spoke and said, you fellows must not talk around in the office or on the street as Stone has his hired sons of B- every where as you can see and the less you talk the better it will be for all of us- Kennedy came to see Hage at this time when they retired for a private consultation which lasted for about half an hour. D could not hear their conversation but think it was in reference to Fowler as Hage said to Kennedy when he was leaving with him that he had better stay where he is for the present, they had expected Fowler this morning, but he did not come.  Murphy received a letter from Thomas, saying the boys are wild about these arrests and there will be trouble now - Murphy was reading this letter to three or four in his room; Kennedy has been in and out of Hages' room a great many times this evening holding short talks with Hage, them leaving and returning this eve about 10pm two were given cause to see Hage.
Completed

from what D could learn, they are from McCook Neb they were intending to stop at this Hotel but Hage said no, you fellows had better stop at the McCoy with Kennedy as this place is too well known and there are too many detectives in and out of hear. D did not learn their names, but one of the men was about 35 years of age dark hair and mustache and will weigh about 170 pounds is about 5 ft 9 inch and wears a dark navy blue suit with black soft hat; the other was smaller with dark hair and heavy mustache and wears a dark suit and still hat and is about the same age of the other. The day clerk Joe Cody has not returned as yet and no one seems to know his whereabouts as D has heard several of the boarders ask the Proprietor his whereabouts, but he assures to be ignorant D saw Hage and Cody talking together in the Hall near Hage's room on the afternoon before Cody left - it seemed to be a confidential talk and was interfered with by someone coming up-stairs, that night Cody left and has not been seen here since, he gave out that some of his people were sick and that he was going home, but no one
Completed

around here believes it for some reason To-night Murphy & Hage went out at about 7:30 PM and did not return until about 9 o'clock. After Hage had the talk with the men D described they went to Hage's room where D could not hear any thing of consequence.
Sunday July 15th 88
To-day at National Hotel
There has been quite a number of caller here to-day, among them a member of unclear men who are as bitter as most of the strikers against the Q management  and particularly denounce Kelly Bowles and Mcunclear who they say are being paid to destroy the Brotherhood and work the officers of the Brotherhood into this dynamite trouble. Frisbee of Aurora is still here and still says that Kelly will have to pay for this, they are very much scared by Bowles confession and all denounce him. D was talking to his brother J.T. Bowles and he says that he would never own him as a brother again, he says I have done all I could for that man, have been on the go night and day for him for more than a week and to think now
Completed

that he would turn against his friends but he says all I care for now is that he doesn't implicate Hage for if he does and makes a full confession the Brotherhood are gone in this part of the country, he says I have only got to talk with him about five minutes, but he is stubborn and will give every thing away, the same two men who I mentioned and described in (D's) report yesterday were with Hage in confidential conversation to-day and the larger of the two doing a great deal of waiting in Hage's room waiting dictated letter for Hage they say that something should be done to teach squealers a lesson, but don't say what is to be done Hage went to the McCoy House about 7:30 last evening and met a large number most of them being strangers often staying there for quite awhile he went to 183 3rd Avenue which is a sporting House remaining there for about two or three hours; D took a long walk with J.T. Bowles to-night going to several saloons on Clark St and State St, he says he has given up all hope for his Brother and that he can now go to hell for al that he cares; Fowler has
Completed

not returned as yet but Hage has received several messages from him Murphy has been in his room very closely to-day, he has had a number of callers but nothing of importance was said of them discussing the confession of Bowles and Kelly who they denounce - they are very much guarded in what they say now and are very suspicious of all not known personally J.T. Bowles saying to D these are times when a fellow can hardly trust himself; Murphy received a letter from Thomas this morning from unclearJoe; unclear saying to keep up, as all the boys there were watching things very very closely and that you must not break down now as all depends upon you and Hage, he says there will be trouble in that part of the country before long as most of the men are getting desperate now since the arrests have been made and that it will be hard work to control most of them now; Kennedy has not been around any to-day or this Evening Bowles and D returned at 12 o'clock and when they came in the Hotel Murphy Hage & a man who looks much like unclear
Completed

(but was not) were talking together at the head of the stairway Hage promised him that he would come to McCoy's Hotel in the morning.
Monday July 16 88
at National Hotel
D. reports that nothing of any importance transpired to-day; most of the men were attending the trial in the U.S. Court Murphy & Hage being in their rooms most all day with the exception of Murphy going to the West side to meet some fireman & switchmen? some place on South Halsted St this afternoon, he was gone about two hours when, he returned he and Hage held a consultation about some letter that had been send out and which Hage said he did not know any thing about and asked Murphy if he had sent it, Murphy said he knew nothing of it; Hage said "there is some scheme in this and we will have to look out, this is the work of the Q. D could not find out what the letter or circular contained but is positive that Hage knows all about it and what he said to Murphy was done for a blind? for two strangers that were standing in the Hall near Hage's room, this evening
Completed

there were a great many here early in the evening but all but Hage went away going to attend a Brotherhood meeting at 111-49th St. J.T. Bowles is still here D had a long talk with him this evening he said I am done with that Brother of min and would not help him out now if I could, he said the Brotherhood will do anything now to assist Bourestein? and Broderick but the rest must look out for them selves, he said I believe I will stay in Chicago now as I have the offer of a job on the Rock Island and believe I will accept it, it all depends what the boys decide on at the meeting to-night he says he would not like to be in the place of the "squealers" if the boys once get a chance at them, he also said if these men are convicted the Q will suffer for it, he then left going up street; the man Frisbee from Aurora has been drinking very much to-day and is very loud in denouncing the way the trial is being conducted and says all we can do is to make the Q suffer for it. Fowler or Thomas have not returned yet, there men
Completed

with Hage each have a sporting woman at 183-185 3rd Ave. D has been with them there several times they spend money very freely for beer & wine and have taken these women to a place they call Bachelors for supper at 11 and 12 o'clock. Hage has a woman who goes m the name of Sadie at #183 3rd Ave she boasts of the amount of money that she gets from him when he comes to see her, he was to see her last night - Fowler's woman is named Minnie she says she can get any thing she wants from him he having paid several bills for her this house is known as the Brotherhood house a great many of the A.T. and unclear men also frequents this house and at 185 Thomas has a woman named Ann who used to be at 183 but went next door to 185; Thomas when here goes there all most every night to see her, all of these men mentioned spend a great deal of money on these women. D was there with J.T.Bowles he seemed very much astonished the way they used Hages. Fowlers and Thomas names? before every one he says Hage had better never let
Completed

another know of this or there will be trouble, this evening every thing is very quiet around the Hotel Hage being in his room and all the rest going to the meeting on 49th St.
Respectfully submitted
Pinkerton's National Detective Agency
By Wm A. Pingerton
Genl Supt West Div
x
Completed

Chicago July 20 1888
HBStone esq
Genl Mangr  CBT & RR
City
Dear Sir:
Following please find report of D.D.
Thursday July 12th '88
To-day in Chicago at the National Hotel D. report that not many called and only a few to see Hage but nothing was done or said of any consequence, they were apparently in the dark as to how Hage and Murphy's case will come out to-morrow, they are very guarded in this talk; Hage saying to Murphy "You must trust no one or we will get the worst of it; Bourisen came in this evening and he and Hage and Kennedy and a new man - a young man of about 25 years of age, smooth face, dark hair and eyes about 5 ft 6 inch tall and weighs about 140 lbs dressed in dark blue suit and wearing soft black hat; they went to Hage's room and would let
Completed

no one in but Murphy for over an hour, when the new man left and was away about 30 minutes then returned to Hage's room, D could not learn his name or where he was from but he came from Aurora with Bounisen?; Kennedy left about 9:30 and did not return - they expected Fowler back this evening but he did not come but will be here to-morrow morning - Murphy rec'd a telegram from Thomas from Galesburgh to-night saying he would leave there either no-night or tom-morrow morning for Kansas City and to keep him posted in regard to the trial - they all seem to be anxious about Fowler's return as he has a great influence over them. D could not get to hear the conversation of Hage, Bounisen?, Kennedy and the new man as they went to Hage's room and it was impossible for D to hear them without exciting suspicion D will try and get one of the new circulars that they have just got out, when Fowler returns D can do more as they will then come to his room to do the talking.
Respectfully submitted
Pinkerton' Natl Detective Agency
By Wm A. Pinkerton
Genl Supt West Div
Completed

Chicago July 21st 1888
H.B. Stone Esq
Genl Mgr. C.B.& Q/ R.R.
City 
Dear Sir:
Following you will please find reports of Opt. D.D.
Thursday July 19th 1888
Today in Chicago at the National Hotel there has been very little going on, the Committee meeting at the McCoy House this morning and again this afternoon. The general feeling among the Advisory Committee is that the strike be declared off but will wait until Hoge & Murphy return to find out the general feeling out side of t Chicago. LeMay says that Beaurisen, Broderick, Goching? and Clark will have the support and sympathy of the Brotherhood in their coming trial, if the Q does not decide to drop it. Goode & Hill are doing the clerical work for Hoge and Murphy during their absence. Kennedy being their advisor in every thing. They are still very suspicious of F.T. Bowles on account
Completed

of his brother and shun him on all occasions, he has commenced to notice it and is very mad at some of the committees. They will do anything to help Beaurisen out of this trouble & Chairman You? is afraid Hoge will be implicated with Beaurisen and Broderick. Kennedy says "You need not be afraid of anything like that for Hoge is to slick to be caught in any trap." They seem to think that Fowler has escaped very well according to Bowles testimony but think if the company & committee come together again that the company will drop the cases against the men arrested, and will not make any more new arrests. This seems to be the general impression. Frisbee from Aurora is still here. He went tot eh Depot with Beaurisen, J.T. Bowles and several others. Beaurisen had a pass for five over the N.W. W. Fowler has not yet returned. Thomas is now in Denver as Goode opened a letter to-day addressed to Hoge from Thomas, and will be back here to-morrow night or Saturday. Martin of Galesbury came early this morning and Opt. has not had an opportunity to hear any of his conversation yet but will tomorrow. Joseph Cody the missing day clerk also came back.
Completed

this morning (this report written morning of the 20th) He said he had been home on account of the sickness of some of his people. There are several arrivals this morning but Opt. has not had a chance to hear any of their conversations as yet. 
Yours Respectfully
Pinkerton's Nat'l. Det. Agency
By W.A.Pinkerton
Gen'l Supt. W. Div.
A.R.
Completed

Chicago July 21 1888
H.B. Stone Esq.
Gen'l. Mg'r C.B. & Q. R.R.
City
Dear Sir:
Following please find reports of Opr. D.D. for Tuesday July 17 and Wednesday July 18th 1888.
Tuesday July 17th 1888
To day in Chicago Opr. reports that there has been a great many at the National Hotel to-day and most of them received their money for July. Hoge paying out a great deal of money Murphy also paying some. Most of the men asked how long they were to hold when Hoge says "We will have this thing settled in less than a week now and we wont get the worst of it." There was a great deal of talking and it was hard for the Opr. to distinguish one voice from the other but one man said "Well teh Q has lots of Sal Soda engines now and it would not take long to cripple every one on the road." Hoge says, "This is no place to talk, the less you have to say the better.
Completed

2
as that is just as he has done us up has been too much talk and not enough work, but we will not get much the worst of this fight, so you fellows must all keep still for awhile and wait and see how things come out. I am going to St. Louis tonight and will be back some time Friday and you must all behave while I am away. There was a great deal of talk many expressing the opinion than the strike should have been declared off a long while ago and among some who do not want it declared off a present. Frisbie and a man names Daniels each made a short speech to the crowd present. Frisbie is one who does not want the strike declared off and says, "Arthur of any one else has no business to interfere with us now. Daniels saying, "Now if you will just let Arthur and the General Committee alone every thing will come out all right, but if you don't, you just might as well go to farming, for the changes are, the way this thing is now and this dynamite-buis ness, we would all be black listed, then what are you to do about it. The Brotherhood cannot up hold any such buis ness and the Public know all that has been done and the Company know a great deal
Completed

more, as we can not tell who is a Detective any more in our own organization as you all know some one has been giving every move we have made away, and it is time this thing ended or our organization will be destroyed & we cannot afford to have that done." Hoge says "We would have won this fight in less than two weeks longer if it had not been for this man Smith and Bowles and some more squealers who I know but have not made them selves known to us yet, but we would have brought the company to our own terms in less than that time. Now we have lost every thing and have to make the best terms possible. I am not worried about my arrest for I will come out of that all right and will keep some of the other boys out." Then there was a general conference among them on Baurisin's & Broderick's cases, Hoge saying "We will bring them through all safe as we will make the Company drop the cases now, but this -- - - ---- of a Bowles, he can take care of himself now." They are very much worried about the arrest of Clark in Galesburg and do not seem to understant it. Hoge left for St. Louis on the evening train telling most of them that he was
Completed

going east but did not. Last night Opr. met several fo the Chairman of the different roads, who are here. It is what they call the Advisory Committee. Opr. talked with Dennison of the Brotherhood from Newark Ohio LeMan Fowler from Burlington and a small man from Bellville Ill, who is the Chairman of the Committee. He is very much in favor of a settlement and says that he advised it from weeks ago, before any of this Dynamite buisness happened. He also Said, "We are in a bad fix now we cannot carry any of these men who were guilty of any of any such work. I told Hoge when I was here before that if some kind of a settlement was not made soon there would be some one get us all into trouble, but he laughed at me, he now sees where he is placed."This man was talking to J.T. Bowles & several others in front of the Hotel. A big man named Young who is also of the Committee spoke in favor of most any terms of settlement so as to clear the Brotherhood. They are to have a meeting to morrow morning at ten oclock in which the whole situation is to be discussed J.T. Bowles is to go to work for the Rock Island R.R. Thomas has not returned yet, Wm Fowler is still away and
Completed

Murphy has been away from the hotel all evening.
Wendesday July, 18th, 1888.
To-Day in Chicago at the National Hotel there are several of the Advisory Committee stopping there among them Chairman You. They held a long and stormy meeting this morning at the McCoy House. Some of the committee being strongly in favor of declaring the strike off now, while others do not want it declared off for a while yet. Chairman You is strongly in favor of declaring it off now. Opr was talking to him after the meeting, he said he thought that they would come to an understanding in a short time Opr. also heard him, LeMay & Young talking. They are in favor of declaring it off if the Company will drop the prosecution of Bourisen and Goding and reinstate the Grievance Committee that is Hoge, Fowler, Murphy & Co. Chairman You says, "If we don't declare this thing off while it wont break the Brotherhood up, it will hurt us so we can never recover. You see how things have been going until now something will have to be done to square us before the public and now we cannot trust our own men as the company have this detectives be-?
Completed

longing to the Brotherhood, what can we do, we must have a reorganization after this thing is settled." LeMay says, "I am not in favor of giving in at the present for it will be a square back down and the public will think that we had to come to terms on account of this dynamite business, that is why I don't want to be hasty about this." Young did not have much to say one way of the other except that the company should drop all the prosecutions. Kennedy came up at this time and stood in the Hall talking to several of them. They all want the Company to stop the prosecution of Hoge, Murphy, Baurisen and Goding which they will insist on especially Hoge's & Murphy's. Chairman You says, "Stone has given the Brotherhood the hardest fight it ever had and the quicker we get the thing settled the better it will be for all of us in the future." They were very much annoyed by the confession of Bowles this after noon and the way he implicated Baurisen, Goding & Clair and seem to think that he joined the Brotherhood for the express purpose of doing what he has done. They are also very much afraid of his brother now and have little to say to him in regards to their places and intentions. They blame the men now under arrest for
Completed

having anything to do with Wilson. Kennedy says, "We might have known that some such a game would be worked by the company but it is too late now to say any thing about it, but we will have to get good Lawyers to defend the boys when it comes to trial, if it ever does." A man named unclear called to see the committee this evening but Opr. did not hear or learn what was said but the man went away apparently satisfied Murphy has not been there to day, he talked of going to Otterman?Ia. for a few days to see his folks. Opr. has not heard any thing from fowler or Thomas yet. Opr. took a walk with Chairman You and Dennison of Newark O. going to several saloons and to the New Haven and going back to the Hotel and meeting most all the rest of them in front of the Hotel when they stood talking until 12 OClock when some went with Kennedy the other going up stairs.
Yours Respectfully
Pinkerton's Nat'l. Det. Agency
By W.A. Pinkerton
Gen'l. Supt. W. Div
A.R.
Completed

Chicago July 23rd 1888
H.B.Stone Esq
Gen'l. Mgr. C.B. & Q R.R.
City
Dear Sir:
Following you will please find report of Opr. D.D.
Saturday, July 21st 1888
Opr. reports that to day in Chicago at the National Hotel there has been a number there to-day to see Fowler and talk with him about what he did in the east. He went as far east as Rochester N.Y. and brought back a sum of money (Ope does not know how much) which he collected from the different divisions in the east. This morning when Opr. got up which was about 6 am he met Fowler walking up and down the hall. Opr. asked him what was the matter as Opr. knew he had not been in bed but a very short time, and he said, "I am very nervous and did not sleep any last night. I believe I am going to be sick." He also said, "These ____ arrests have upset me I don't know but what they will be after me next."
Completed

Opr. said. "Oh there is no danger of you being arrested, do you think?" He said "Weill it is -- hard to tell, there are so many squealers now that they might try to implicate me as the company knows that I have done all I could in a legitimate was to carry on this strike and they might with their ---- Detectives try to get me in trouble the same as they have Beaurisen and Goding." He asked Opr once before any arrests were made but Opr said nothing about it in his report if he knew where Noblesville ind. was and Opr. told him he did not as he had never heard of the town at that time. Opr. had it in his notes but never looked at it in making his reports. This was about the first of July. This afternoon they were most all down to the McCoy House with the exception of Fowler who went down to see some of the A.T. & S.F. R.R. men in their yards and at their Depot. At 11:30 Thomas came in from Denver and reported that all the man as far as he saw were not willing to give up the strike and that Hoge and Murphy could not do any good now as they had their suspicions that the Company were at the bottom of sending them there and that they were not going to give up until they had too as they had
Completed

stuck this far and could stick until this fall. There was nothing of interest until to night when there were a great many around the Hotel and in front talking to Fowler, Thomas and Kennedy who seems to be the center of attraction with all of them. They now use his room at the McCoy House as a sort of committee room. J. T. Bowles left to-night at 8:30 for Logansport, but will return on monday. Before the left he and Fowler held a long private conversation on the side walk which Opr. was unable to hear. Thomas and Opr. took a walk this afternoon and he told Opr. that if the strike was not over in a very short time that he was going into the saloon buisiness in St. Joe with his Brother-in-Law.He said, "I don't suppose they will take any of the Committee men back any way so I had better look out for my self." At about the o'clock Fowler Thomas and Opr. went up tot he New Haven saloon and from there took a cable car on State St. and went to 183 and 185 Third Ave. Fowler got very full and Thomas went into 185 and remained in there with his woman until about three oclock this morning when they started for the Hotel. they were also joined by a saloon keeper named Jerry Healy
Completed

who keeps a saloon on Third Ave opposite the Polk St. Depot. They spent their money very freely with the women and at the different saloons. Hoge's woman wanted to know very particular when he would return as she wanted to tell him something of great importance to him and all. She would not tell it until she saw Hoge as it was of more interest to him than any one else. They then returned to the Hotel where nothing more of interest occurred. Thomas says there will be over three hundred Engineers and Firemen here next week to attend a general Meeting.
Yours Respectfully
Pinkertons Nat. Det. Agency
By W.A. Pinkerton 
Gen'l. Supt. W. Div
A.R.
Completed

Chicago July 24th 1888
HB Stone Esq.
Genl. Mangr W.B. & Q. R.R.
Chicago
Dear Sir,
Today please find the report of Opr. M.D.M dated at Chicago Tuesday July 17th 1888.
Today in Chicago. Opr went to the National Hotel and inquired of the Clerk if G.M. Sargeant was stopping there. learned he was not but that he might be found at the Grand Pacific. Opr looked around and could not see him at the National so he went to the Grand Pacific and examined the Hotel Register saw the name of P.M. Arthur registered from Cleveland? and assigned to room 111 So Opr stepped outside and a man came up to him put his hand on Opr shoulder and said this is John Dignan. Opr looked at him and saw at once that he knew the man to be an Engineer from the Jersey Central Road by name of Scott. he asked me a good many questions which Opr ans. all right. Then Opr asked him about himself and found he was out of a Job and was looking for work. The man said the Strike was not over yet and if it would be settled it would take all this week to do it. Scott then took Opr to the front door of the Hotel looking East and
Completed

pointed out a window over in the Post Office and said in that Corner Window. You can see the Squealers. there are some 4 of them in there and one man by the name of Kelly is a fine Bitch he is the worst of the whole lot. that he swore falsely. By this time Hoge and Murphy came along and Op was introduced to Hoge but did no have much chance to talk with him. Hoge said the Trouble is not settled as yet. and it will be some time before it will be settled if things dont take a different Turn. pretty soon. said that he and Murphy were to leave town this afternoon. and that P.M. was here now and would attend to matters for a short time Opr remained around those who were talking to Scott, Scott Sullivan Connors. and self. had some drinks at the National Hotel Bar. and about 5 p.m. Opr saw P.M. Arthur talking to Geo Groman Chairman of General Grievance Committee on Union Pacific Road Scott informed Opr that Groman had just arrived from Omaha. and the men on that road are in favor of a General unclear. and that on all the Western roads running out of Chicago but said it was all talk that they would never to that. After Opr saw Arthur and Groman separate. Opr attempted to talk to him, There were some 3 or 4 Reporters talking to him Opr waited and had a few words with him. he wanted to know what Opr was doing there Opr told him he was just from the West, and he said "don't stop around here. all good men must keep away from here at present. Opr told him he intended to remain for a week or so and then I was going East. he said he intended to leave the City tonight. but did not say where he was going. but Opr understood from the men on the U.P. and N.Western that Arthur and
Completed

unclear were to attend a Genearl Meeting of the 4 orders of Raid Road. Men. at St Paul and see if they could not consolidate the Brotherhood of Breakmen Switchmen Firemen and Engineers. unclear under one head and unclear by one man here in the West __ The man Groman will talk but little and is very careful what he says. While Opr was talking with Arthur unclearman came up and called Arthur away. Therefore Opr went and talked to Scott who informed Opr he had done nothing since the Brotherhood strike in Brooklyn and that he was going to as P.M for a letter and was then waiting to see him. Opr noticed Arhur and Groman went up stair and as Opr noticed no Rail Road men around. Opr told scott that he would go home on the West side. 
Wednesday July 18th 1888.
Opr again called at the National Hotel at 9 am. found none of the Rail Road Men around so he went to the Grand Pacific Hotel remained there a few minutes looking over the Morning papers. then left returned again at 10:30 A.M. Met Engineer Hoffman from Kansas City and Eugene Scott from New York. who told Opr he had had an interview with P.M. Arthur last Evening and got a letter from him that reads in this way. The Bearer W.C. Scott is a Locomotion Engineer in good standing and I can cheerfully recommend him to any one wanting his services and Signed P.M. Arthur G. C. and under that the man Geo Vroman Chairman of the General Grievance Committee of W. P. States. who is personally acquainted with this Man Scott. for
Completed

the past 8 years and knows him to be a good Engineer In report of Opr. Yesterday I mentioned the Man Vroman as Groman. his name is Vroman. Scott told Opr that P.M. Arthur got a Telegram from S. Paul stating that Every thing was quiet there now. and the meeting that was to be held there, was postponed until some future date. Thereupon Arthur Vroman Scott and Sullivan went to Michigan Southern Depot and saw Arthur away. Sullivan is an Engineer on the North Western running from Chicago to unclear Scott also told Opr. and cautioned to keep the thing still. That! Hoge and Murphy started out on a Trip over the entire 2 System to take a Vote of the Men. on declaring the Strike off or continuing it on certain conditions. the conditions Scott would not mention. when asked he said he would not know. There was some men here from the Brooklyn Elevated Road that scabbed there and he told Opr he was going to put the men into it as soon as Court was over. During the Evidence of Bowles. Hoffman and Self were sitting together. Hoffman said he would like to have him (Bowles) down in Kansas City some dark night. That he knew him to be from West Va and would not believe him on the Gallows. and that he was nothing more than a Horse thief in his Young days. Every time David The Sawyer would corner Bowles. he (Bowles) would take a drink of Water and Hoffman would say his water was getting low and make all manner of fun of the witness Bowles. he (Hoffman) also said Bowles might just as well leave the Country for he would never get along here for all the men were on to him. After leaving the Court
Completed

room at 5 p.m. Hoffman Scott Sullivan Wade and Sell returned to National Hotel had some drinks and cigars Opr noticed six or seven men get together and talk very low. the Scot came over to where Opr was and said he knew one of those men from Brooklyn Elevated Road to be bought off for $100.00 paid by the B of S E. and now he expected he come out here to make a stake and if he could stop him he would or put some of the Q goys on to him Thereupon Opr discontinued until morning
Respectfully Submitted
Pinkertons Natl Det Agcy.
per Wm A Pinkerton
Genl Supt. Western Div.
Completed

Chicago July .24. 1888.
H.B.Stone Esq.
Genl. Mangr W.B.& Q.R.R.
City
Dear Sir.
Following find report of Opr. M. D. J. dated at Chicago July 20th 21st & 22d
Today in Chicago Opr went to the National Hotel at 10.a.m. Met Scott. Carroll and one of the 9 men named Daniels from the B&M Road. -- Scott introduced me to the latter. Opr asked how matters were shaping this morning, and what prospects there were for a Settlement was informed that every division of the Brotherhood Voted to Carry on the Strike until the Officers of the Burlington would do what was right with the men they did not like to see their men prosecuted unjustly. but the Road would have to make some concessions to the men. Scott then said the rules are in all cases to pay the Striking Engineers and Firemen $60 & $40.00 per mo. for 3 months from the General Fund but in this Case. all divisions throughout the Country Voted to Carry on the Strike by assessment on the Members. and said that most every man gives from 5.00 and upwards every month toward keeping those men and as long as they do that they can hold theRoad down. Scott said that George Vroman told him
Completed

that the Grievance Committee from all roads in the Country had been sent Invitations to be here on the 22d but he thought from what he heard from the East none of them would come. as they say they will abide by what the Western Men does in the case. and that just as soon as Hoge and Murphy returns with their Official report then the Committee will get Together and do something for the future, and what will be done no one will know. but as far as they can see now the Strike will on. The Opr and Carroll went up to the Michigan Southern Depot and called on Master Mechanic Harkney of the Santa. Got return papers and made up his mind to get out of Town by tomorrow, Opr returned to the Grand Pacific Hotel Again ata 12. Noon. remained there until 1:30 p.m. then left, returned again at 3 p.m. saw Hoge's son there on the steps of the National Hotel Stairs, and asked him where his Father was and he said he did not know. just then Opr saw Scott (d:30) Wroman. and unclear from Ft. Wayne. talking in the Hall Way did not venture near them. Scott came to Opr afterwards and wanted to know when Opr was going home to N.Y. State Scott evidently thinks Opr's Family are in Kingston N.Y. Opr told him that in a probability he would go home about next Tuesday or Wednesday. that he did not know for sure when he would go East, that he wanted to see the Strike settled in favor of the men before he left so they separated to meet tomorrow and hear the Trial at the Armory.
Saturday July 21st 1888.
Opr further reports that 11 a.m. he went around to the Grand Pacific and National Hotel. and Met Engineer Sullivan
Completed

of the North Western Road. Coones from Omaha Flynn from the Belt Road. outside the City. Ducey from the q? Collins from Elkhart and Scott. found that some of those men were lookin for jobs and are waiting around here in hopes of getting on. Opr inquired if any one knew when the Committee would meet here. and learned that no one know. or would know until Hoge and Murphy returned here and made their report. they say every thing rests with Hoge and Murphy. as a good many men are of the opinion that Hoge could have settled this Trouble before now if he had wanted to Scott said that Stone would have to resign his position with the Burlington if the Directors could get any other Man to Step in and run the Road Straighten up with the men and have them all return to work. Flynn spoke up and said he would be satisfied to see if 1/2 of the men back and the men arrested let go with the Exceptions of Bowles and Smith - he wanted to see those S-s of B-s strung up Then scott wanted Opr to come and attend the Trial at the Armory this morning, so they took Op up there. and found the Trial put off until Afternoon. They returned to the Hotel and remained there until 1 p.m. Op then left and called back at 2 p.m. found the same men there with Bowles telling them that Bowles, his brother, cannot be blamed for this trouble. Although he said "(if. My Brother") had not come out and told what he knew he would have him out of Prison in a day or two, after he gave the thing away. and he then said that he did not know where the thing would End. Opr and the balance of the party they went to the armory and remained there during the Trial. While
Completed

at the Trial Scott who sat to the left of Opr. would frequently say that if he "Scott" had a brother like that man Bowles he would kill the S___ of a B__ Bowles Brother sat in front of Opr. and Scott said that the brother upheld Bowles in what he was doing. A Young Man & an Engineer sat behind us, and they would say that Bowles Evidence was manufactured for this occasion, as he swore different at the Previous Trial. -- On the way back to the Hotel from the Armory Opr heard Ducey and Flinn say. that Bauerisen was very foolish to take in any Stranger into such a trap as that was. and that it was hard to know who Your Friends were now. as most Every Engineer Comes in to or around the Grand Pacific or National is shaddowed by Detectives. The party then stopped in front of the Grand Pacific to talk to a man who was a Stranger to Opr, therefore Opr continued on to the West Side - Opr says there is to be a Union meeting at St Joe on the 24th of the present Month and that he Noticed some Eastern Delegates here at the National Hotel ready to attend. Opr says it is hard to get into any of their private meetings as they call them. They say the Committee is Meeting now and no one is allowed in, so there is not much use stopping around there longer.
Sunday. July 22d 1888
Opr further reports That he went to the Naional Hotel at 10 a.m. and met Scott and was informed by him that there were a few men in Hoge's Room up stairs and asked Opr if he had seen the Chicago World. that there as a good piece in it about Bowles and Stone. Just
Completed

then a man came up and wanted to know if there were any engineers Around. Opr and Scott answered and said they were Engineers. He then presented his Traveling Card, and it was from Rochester N.Y. and his name was Geo Wilson. he also had a letter from the Chief Saying the bearer Wilson was Elected Delegate to Attend the Union meeting to be held at St Joe. on the 24th. Opr asked him what the Eastern Men thought of this trouble and he said they were willing to carry the men along by paying assessments until the Company would give in they then went up to Hoges Room. And then Bro Wilson was Introduced to Sullivan Hogan. Bowles and others, They talked by themselves and Opr and Scott remained there for a few moments and during that time several Strangers came in and wanted to know where the Meeting was going to be held Scott told them that there was no meeting today as Hoge and Murphy were not here. and until they would return there would be nothing done. or until after the Union Meeting at St Joe. Scott Told Opr that he was going to leave here about Tuesday for Omaha or some place in the West. and Wants Opr to tell the boys in the East that I saw him and he was still looking for a job. as there was then nothing going on. Opr left and returned again at 3 p.m. found things quiet no one around. Opr understood from Scott and Sullivan that there is to be a meeting called at Omaha for the purpose off getting all the members of teh K of S. and all the Rail Road Brotherhood and have it understood that any Merchant that gets his Freight over the Q. Road and wont stop shipping or receiving any Freight over
Completed

the Q. road the men will cease dealing with Them and they said that the men would do everything to get Even now. Thereupon Opr discontinued for the day.
Yours Truly. Pinkertons Natl Det Agcy.
per. W.A.Pinkerton
Gen Supt. Western Div.

Chicago July 24" -- 88
H.B. Stone Esq
General Mgr @ B&Q Ry
Adams St
City
Dear Sir
Following you will please find report of Opr DD at the National Hotel
Friday July 10" - 88
There were quite a number of callers today at the National Hotel to see the advisory committee. most of them being from this city and Aurora. There is a very strong feeling against Hoge amongst some of the men who even go so far as to say that he has played unclear false There is also a bad feeling existing amongst the Advisory Committee. LeMay and  Young being very much opposed to the way in which Hoge has conducted the strike and say openly that there is some thing wrong somewhere, that it is all foolishness for Hoge & Murphy to go over the line, that they cannot do anything now to influence the men in the west. And Engineer who came in yesterday named
Completed

Rice said that the strike should not be declared off at this time. he talked very bitterly against the C.B.&Q. Ry to several of the committee and also against those who favored a settlement. He and Martin of Galesbury seem to share the same opinions. Martin said "we have them and they are scared to death, we can make them come to our terms if we just hold out a little while longer". There was a general meeting in Kennedy's room at the McCoy Hotel today. the Opr does not know what was done except that it was decided to stick to the men now under arrest with the exception of Bowles adn Smith. They don't see to think any too much of unclear, they claim he has been talking too much to the Dist Atty. Fowler came in at 9 pm tonight but went immediately to McCoy's to see Kennedy & Martin. An hour later he walked up in front of the National and told the opt that he had been down in New York State to see some of his relations. He asked the Opt if he had heard anything of him (Fowler) going to be arrested. The Opt said "No, what would they arrest you for"? "Oh" he said, you know they think I am dynamiter because Bowles came to see Hoge and myself while we were at the Grand Pacific. I did not pay much attention to what Bowls was
Completed

saying at that time, he was talking more to Kelly than he was to Hoge or me". Cautioning he said "they would raise hell if they knew that Bowles came to my room here at the National and wrote several letters using my letter heads and then sleeping in my room for several hours. he further said "I dont know any thing of this dynamite business and think it is a put up job by Bowles, Smith and the Pinkertons, that if as much dynamite was used as they testified to, they could have blown up every train on the "Q" without any trouble. He then went to look for Martin & Rice but soon returned and suggested to the Opt that they go down to Third Ave to see if Martin & Rice were there. The Opt complied so they went to Nos 183 & 185 Third Ave, Upon entering Hoge's girl ran up to Folwer and said that there were some men there early in the evening who said that you (F) and Hoge were to be arrested and they were going to do all in their power to rail road you to the penitentiary. After this Fowler was very nervous and said to Opt "what if they shadowed us down here, it would be a picnic for the Company to bring up that against me if arrested, that all that they had Goding for was in hopes he could not give bond and rather than stay in jail squeal." At
Completed

about 12.30 they left Third Ave and returned to the hotel. Fowler was very nervous and uneasy. he said to Opt "I believe I will go and see Kennedy before I go to bed" he then went to McCoy's hotel and remained there about an hour. In the course of conversation Fowler said that Thomas would be here tomorrow sure. While at No 183 Third Avenue Sadie (Hoge's girl) called Fowler out on the porch and held a long whispered conversation. This woman is very keen and notices everything that is said for and against the brotherhood and advises them of it Tomorrow afternoon there will be a general meeting at McCoy's of all the brotherhood men interested in the strike. The Opt also talked with Chairman You who is in favor of a peaceful settlement. Of Hoge he said "we are going to sift these charges down and if he is guilty we wont whitewash him" He then asked the Opt if he had seen the article in the Cincinnati Enquirer of today. The Opt said he had not thereupon Fowler went and got one and showed the Opt the article that charges Hoge with being false to the brotherhood Some committeemen here interrupted and no more was said--
Yours Respectfully
Pinkerton's Nat Det Agcy
by Wm A. Pinkerton
GEn Supt West Div

Dear Sir:--
Following you will please find report of Opr D.D.
Sunday July 22nd 1888
Opr. reports that there has not been but very little going on at the National Hotel today most all of the men going away Saturday night to spendSunday. J.L. Bowles did not go away Saturday night as he missed the train Opr. was talking to him to-day and he said, "I am going to work for the Rock Island on Tues day or Wednes day if some of these fellows don't go and interfere". Opr. asked him in what way any of the Brotherhood would interfere in his securing a place, and he said. "Well I cannot see why they would either but still they are very suspicious of me.
